         The Mutual Fund Show: ‘Arbitrage Fund Best Fit For A Risk-Averse Investor’
      













BQ Desk

                  
                  @bloombergquint
                  


Niraj Shah

                  
                  @_nirajshah
                  






          15 Jun 2017, 08:48 am
        

          15 Jun 2017, 08:48 am
        














 


















Editor's Choice



 















Deal To Sell Fortis Healthcare To Malaysia’s IHH Alive And Kicking: Exclusive 




 Consolidation Coming? This Time In District Cooperative Banks... 




 Reliance Deja Vu: The Return Of The ‘Monsoon Hungama’ Offer 




  Chandrasekaran To ‘Prune The Portfolio’ Of Tata Group Companies  




 ONGC-HPCL Deal: Can The Government Get Away With Avoiding An Open Offer? 
























 





















Arbitrage funds are the best fit for a risk-averse investor, said Harsha Upadhyaya, chief investment officer (equity) at Kotak Mahindra Asset Management Company.“Without getting affected by market volatility, you are able to generate higher returns than a fixed deposit and it is tax free,” Upadhyaya said while recommending arbitrage funds on BloombergQuint’s The Mutual Fund Show.Upadhyaya also talked about the benefits of investing in liquid funds over fixed deposits and should one choose lump-sum or systematic investment plans.






Here are edited excerpts from the conversation.






What about the option of liquid funds versus fixed deposit?Liquid fund is not a comparable product. A liquid fund has no lock-in; if you invest today and wish to withdraw tomorrow, you can do that. It’s more of a savings bank deposit than fixed deposit. I cannot comment on how the returns will be in future, but as per past experience, they have been slightly better than those on fixed deposits on a post-tax basis.






Are the liquid funds subject to any tax?Yes, they are and that is the advantage of equity arbitrage funds, which are not subject to any tax if you hold them for 12 months.






We had a few requests from people in terms of recommendations that they would want. Firstly, a recommendation for someone who is a risk averse investor. What kind of an equity fund should he choose? For a risk-averse investor, I would assume that he wants to take zero risk on the market volatility. In that case, he can come into the arbitrage fund. These are essentially equity products. They have the same taxation as equity products, which is definitely an advantage. So, any returns coming from that fund post 12 months has zero tax. Also, the dividend coming out of that fund, which is mostly regular in most of the arbitrage funds, is also tax-free. So, what it essentially does is: with the money that comes from the investors, we buy stock of a particular company—let’s say company ABC. We buy 1,000 shares of ABC and go and hedge 1,000 shares of ABC with its own derivative. So, there is no market risk. Irrespective of market ups and downs, this fund is going to give you the spread that was locked in at the initiation between the cash price and the futures price of a particular company. So, it generally moves in line with short-term interest rates. The advantage is that there is no tax. If you hold it for 12 months, you don’t pay a tax. Without getting affected by market volatility, you are able to generate higher returns than a fixed deposit and it is tax free.






Is it about a 30 percent higher return than what a fixed deposit can give you?Yes, potentially.






If you save for more than 12 months,  there is arbitrage fund. I do believe that there is a Kotak Equity Arbitrage Fund, which over a five-year period has given returns northwards of 45 percent.Yes. Cumulatively, 8 percent-odd on a CAGR basis, which is again tax-free. None of the fixed deposits will actually give you that and it has zero risk on the market.






 Infrastructure now seems to be the next big theme, but a lot of companies have already given good returns. Can people now invest in infrastructure funds?Let us first talk about thematic funds. We have infrastructure funds, but a lot of companies have different themes they invest into. An investor needs to understand that these themes do not generate wealth consistently over a period of time. But if the investment theme works in a span of five years, seven years or a decade, you will earn more money than a diversified basket.
At the same time, since the funds are pertinent to a particular theme or sector, the risks are greater than those in a diversified fund. So, usually we suggest investors not to invest more than 5 or 10 percent of their investment. We believe that even in case of infrastructure. 
There is enough policy push from the government these days. The pace of some of the projects handled by the government has significantly increased. There seems to be a clear 3 to 5 year course in terms of how this industry can shape up. 
If you look at our portfolio, we are focused on studying cash flow generation, not much of leverage on the balance sheet. It need not necessarily be just infrastructure, it can be allied sectors. For instance, cement is an allied industry. So, we are essentially looking for companies that have a bigger canvas to work in the next 4 to 5 years in the infrastructure space and also have a steady cash flow generation, very strong financials, etc.























